<p><ent>Wilt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wilt
<hw>Wilt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wilting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Written also <ets>welt</ets>, a
modification of <ets>welk</ets>.]</ety> <def>To begin to wither; to lose
freshness and become flaccid, as a plant when exposed when exposed to
drought, or to great heat in a dry day, or when separated from its root;
to droop;. to wither.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wilt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wilt
<hw>Wilt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to begin to
wither; to make flaccid, as a green plant.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to cause to languish; to depress or destroy
the vigor and energy of.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Despots have <qex>wilted</qex> the human race into sloth and
imbecility.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. T. Dwight.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wilton carpet</ent>⟦br⟧
